Seasonal plots

  labs(
    y = "$ (millions)",
    title = "Australian antidiabetic drug sales"
  )

  labs(y = "$ (millions)",
       title = "Seasonal plot: Antidiabetic drug sales")

Electricity demand graphs

as_tibble(vic_elec) %>%
  group_by(Date = floor_date(Time, "day")) %>%
  summarise(
    Demand = mean(Demand),
    Temperature = mean(Temperature)
  ) %>%
  as_tsibble(index = Date) %>%
  autoplot(Demand)

There is a peak at +7000MW at the beginning of 2014. Curious.

as_tibble(vic_elec) %>%
  group_by(Date = floor_date(Time, "day")) %>%
  summarise(
    Demand = mean(Demand),
    Temperature = mean(Temperature)
  ) %>%
  filter(Demand > 6500)

  1. Download the file tute1.csv from the book website, open it in Excel (or some other spreadsheet application), and review its contents. You should find four columns of information. Columns B through D each contain a quarterly series, labelled Sales, AdBudget and GDP. Sales contains the quarterly sales for a small company over the period 1981-2005. AdBudget is the advertising budget and GDP is the gross domestic product. All series have been adjusted for inflation.

  as_tsibble(index = Quarter)

  1. USgas
us_total <- USgas::us_total %>%
  as_tsibble(index = year, key = state)
new_england <- c(
  "Maine", "Vermont", "New Hampshire", "Massachusetts",
  "Connecticut", "Rhode Island"
)

us_total %>%
  filter(state %in% new_england) %>%
  ggplot(

  1. Tourism.xlsx
tourism_xl <- readxl::read_excel("tourism.xlsx") %>%
  mutate(Quarter = yearquarter(Quarter)) %>%
  as_tsibble(index = Quarter, key = c("Region", "State", "Purpose"))
tourism_xl %>%

The magnitude of the seasonality is a lot higher for NZ and the UK. Less so for Japan and the US. All countries seem to follow an increasing trend, except for flights coming from Japan: it peaked in the mid 90s, and has decreased steadily ever since.

aus_arrivals %>%
  gg_season(y = Arrivals)

Arrivals from the UK (and the US?) are noticeably higher in Q1 and Q4. Understandable, since it’s winter in the northern hemisphere. For NZ, we observe the opposite.

aus_arrivals %>%
  gg_subseries(y = Arrivals)

It seems arrivals from the UK actually began decreasing a few years ago.
There are some peaks in arrivals from the US at the end of the 80s and the 90s.

It gets noticeably higher in November & December. Also in March, and sometimes during the summer?

Same observation.

Same observation as before : December has the highest turnover, compared to every other month.

Unsurprisingly, there is (very) significant positive autocorrelation.
